class=3D"js-post-issue grid--cell s-btn s-btn__unset c-pointer p= y6 mx-auto" href=3D"https://stackoverflow.com/posts/23277366/timeline" data= -shortcut=3D"T" data-ks-title=3D"timeline" data-controller=3D"s-tooltip" da= ta-s-tooltip-placement=3D"right" aria-label=3D"Timeline" aria-describedby= =3D"--stacks-s-tooltip-mhbqo4j1"><svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"mln2 mr= 0 svg-icon iconHistory" width=3D"19" height=3D"18" viewBox=3D"0 0 19 18"><p= ath d=3D"M3 9a8 8 0 113.73 6.77L8.2 14.3A6 6 0 105 9l3.01-.01-4 4-4-4h3L3 9= zm7-4h1.01L11 9.36l3.22 2.1-.6.93L10 10V5z"></path></svg></a><div id=3D"--s= tacks-s-tooltip-mhbqo4j1" class=3D"s-popover s-popover__tooltip pe-none" ar= ia-hidden=3D"true" role=3D"tooltip">Show activity on this post.<div class= =3D"s-popover--arrow"></div></div> </div> </div> =20 <div class=3D"answercell post-layout--right"> =20 <div class=3D"s-prose js-post-body" itemprop=3D"text"> <blockquote> <p>What's the main reason for choosing Red black trees instead of AVL tre= es?</p> </blockquote> <p>Both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red%E2%80%93black_tree" re= l=3D"noreferrer">red-black trees</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or= g/wiki/AVL_tree" rel=3D"noreferrer">AVL trees</a> are the most commonly use= d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-balancing_binary_search_tre= e" rel=3D"noreferrer">balanced binary search trees</a> and they support ins= ertion, deletion and look-up in guaranteed <code>O(logN) time</code>. Howev= er, there are following points of comparison between the two:</p> <ul> <li>AVL trees are more rigidly balanced and hence provide faster look-ups. = Thus for a look-up intensive task use an AVL tree.</li> <li>For an insert intensive tasks, use a Red-Black tree.</li> <li>AVL trees store the balance factor at each node. This takes <code>O(N)<= /code> extra space. However, if we know that the keys that will be inserted= in the tree will always be greater than zero, we can use the sign bit of t= he keys to store the colour information of a red-black tree. Thus, in such = cases red-black tree takes no extra space.</li> </ul> <blockquote> <p>What are the application of Red black tree?</p> </blockquote> <p>Red-black trees are more general purpose. They do relatively well on add= , remove, and look-up but AVL trees have faster look-ups at the cost of slo= wer add/remove. Red-black tree is used in the following:</p> <ul> <li>Java: <a href=3D"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/jav= a.base/java/util/TreeSet.html" rel=3D"noreferrer"><code>java.util.TreeMap</= code></a>, <a href=3D"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/ja= va.base/java/util/TreeSet.html" rel=3D"noreferrer"><code>java.util.TreeSet<= /code></a></li> <li>C++ STL (in most implementations): map, multimap, multiset</li> <li>Linux kernel: completely fair scheduler, linux/rbtree.h</li> </ul> </div> <div class=3D"mt24"> <div =3D"s-popover--arrow"></div></div> </div> </div> =20 <div class=3D"answercell post-layout--right"> =20 <div class=3D"s-prose js-post-body" itemprop=3D"text"> <p>Try reading this <a href=3D"http://discuss.fogcreek.com/joelonsoftware/d= efault.asp?cmd=3Dshow&ixPost=3D22948" rel=3D"noreferrer">article</a></p= > <p>It offers some good insights on differences, similarities, performance, = etc.</p> <p>Here's a quote from the article:</p> <blockquote> <p>RB-Trees are, as well as AVL trees, self-balancing. Both of them provide= O(log n) lookup and insertion performance.</p> <p>The difference is that RB-Trees guarantee O(1) rotations per insert oper= ation. That is what actually costs performance in real implementations.</p> <p>Simplified, RB-Trees gain this advantage from conceptually being 2-3 tre= es without carrying around the overhead of dynamic node structures. Physica= lly RB-Trees are implemented as binary trees, the red/black-flags simulate = 2-3 behaviour</p> </blockquote> <p>As far as my own understanding goes, AVL trees and RB trees are not very= far off in terms of performance. An RB tree is simply a variant of a B-tre= e and balancing is implemented differently than an AVL tree.</p> </div> <div class=3D"mt24"> <div class=3D"grid fw-wrap ai-start jc-end gs8 gsy"> <time also O(= 1) rotation per insertion. For RB-tree and AVL - one insertion may have 1 o= r 0 rotations. If rotation happens, the algorithms stop. If it doesn't happ= en, usually, algorithms continue to check/repaint nodes from bottom to the = root of the tree. So, sometimes rotation O(1) can be better because it elim= inates scanning remaining items O(log(n)). Because AVL tree, in average, ma= kes more rotation, AVL tree is, usually, has better balance ~1.44 log(N) th= an RB-tree 2 log(N).</span> =20 =E2=80=93 <a href=3D"https://stackoverflow.com/users/374845/sergey-sha= ndar" title=3D"2,259 reputation" class=3D"comment-user">Sergey Shandar</a> <span class=3D"comment-date" dir=3D"ltr"><a class=3D"commen= t-link" href=3D"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13852870/red-black-tree= -over-avl-tree#comment83803761_13852913"><span title=3D"2018-01-23 17:18:11= Z, License: CC BY-SA 3.0" class=3D"relativetime-clean">Jan 23 '18 at 17:18<= /span></a></span> <span title=3D"this comment was edited 1 time"> <svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"va-text-bott= om o50 svg-icon iconPencilSm" width=3D"14" height=3D"14" viewBox=3D"0 0 14 = 14"><path d=3D"m11.1 1.71 1.13 1.12c.2.2.2.51 0 .71L11.1 4.7 9.21 2.86l1.17= -1.15c.2-.2.51-.2.71 0zM2 10.12l6.37-6.43 1.88 1.88L3.88 12H2v-1.88z"></pat= h></svg> </span> </div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> <div id=3D"comments-link-13852913" data-rep=3D"50" data-reg=3D"true= "> <a class=3D"js-add-link comments-link disabled-link" ti= tle=3D"Use comments to ask for more information or suggest improvements. performance has improved over th= e years and now the main reason to use red-black trees over AVL would be no= t having access to a good AVL implementation since they are slightly less c= ommon perhaps because they are not covered in CLRS.</p> <p>Both trees are now considered forms of <a href=3D"http://sidsen.azureweb= sites.net//papers/rb-trees-talg.pdf" rel=3D"noreferrer">rank-balanced trees= </a> but red-black trees are consistently slower by <a href=3D"https://benp= faff.org/papers/libavl.pdf" rel=3D"noreferrer">about 20% in real world test= s</a>. Or even 30-40% slower when <a href=3D"https://refactoringlightly.wor= dpress.com/2017/10/29/performance-of-avl-red-black-trees-in-java/" rel=3D"n= oreferrer">sequential data is inserted</a>.</p> <p>So people who have studied red-black trees but not AVL trees tend to cho= ose red-black trees. =3D"s-popover--arrow"></div></div> </div> </div> =20 <div class=3D"answercell post-layout--right"> =20 <div class=3D"s-prose js-post-body" itemprop=3D"text"> <p>Other answers here sum up the pros & cons of RB and AVL trees well, = but I found this difference particularly interesting:</p> <blockquote> <p>AVL trees do not support constant <strong>amortized update cost</stron= g> [but red-black trees do]</p> </blockquote> <p>Source: <a href=3D"http://people.mpi-inf.mpg.de/~mehlhorn/ftp/Toolbox/So= rtedSequences.pdf" rel=3D"nofollow noreferrer">Mehlhorn & Sanders (2008= )</a> (section 7.4)</p> <p>So, while both RB and AVL trees guarantee O(log(N)) worst-case time for = lookup, insert and delete, restoring the AVL/RB property <em>after</em> ins= erting or deleting a node can be done in O(1) <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped= ia.org/wiki/Amortized_analysis" rel=3D"nofollow noreferrer">amortized time<= /a> for red-black trees.</p> </div> <div class=3D"mt24"> <div class=3D"grid fw-wrap data-s-tooltip-placement=3D"right" title=3D"Loading wh= en this answer was accepted=E2=80=A6" tabindex=3D"0" role=3D"note" aria-lab= el=3D"Accepted"> <div class=3D"ta-center"> <svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"svg-icon iconCheckma= rkLg" width=3D"36" height=3D"36" viewBox=3D"0 0 36 36"><path d=3D"m6 14 8 8= L30 6v8L14 30l-8-8v-8z"></path></svg> </div> </div> =20 <a class=3D"js-post-issue grid--cell s-btn s-btn__unset c-pointer p= y6 mx-auto" href=3D"https://stackoverflow.com/posts/33145069/timeline" data= -shortcut=3D"T" data-ks-title=3D"timeline" data-controller=3D"s-tooltip" da= ta-s-tooltip-placement=3D"right" aria-label=3D"Timeline" aria-describedby= =3D"--stacks-s-tooltip-neffx5oe"><svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"mln2 mr= 0 svg-icon iconHistory" width=3D"19" height=3D"18" viewBox=3D"0 0 19 18"><p= ath d=3D"M3 9a8 8 0 113.73 6.77L8.2 14.3A6 6 0 105 9l3.01-.01-4 4-4-4h3L3 9= zm7-4h1.01L11 9.36l3.22 2.1-.6.93L10 10V5z"></path></svg></a><div id=3D"--s= tacks-s-tooltip-neffx5oe" class=3D"s-popover s-popover__tooltip pe-none" ar= ia-hidden=3D"true" role=3D"tooltip">Show activity on this post.<div class= =3D"s-popover--arrow"></div></div> </div> </div> =20 <div class=3D"answercell post-layout--right"> =20 <div class=3D"s-prose js-post-body" itemprop=3D"text"> <p>Programmers generally don't like to dynamically allocate memory. The problem with the avl tree is that for "n" elements you need atleast log= 2(log2(n))...(height->log2(n)) bits to store the height of the tree! So when you are handling enormous data you cannot be sure of how many bits = to allot for storing height at each node.</p> <p>For instance if you use 4 bytes int (32 bits) for storing height. Maximu= m height can be : 2^32 and hence Maximum number of elements you can store i= n the tree is 2^(2^32) --(seems to be very big but in this age of data noth= ing is too big I guess). And hence if you over shoot this limit you have to= dynamically allocate more space for storing height. </p> <p>This is an answer suggested by a professor at my university which seemed= reasonable to me! Hope I make sense.</p> <p>Edits:The AVL trees are more balanced compared to Red Black Trees, but t= hey may cause more rotations during insertion and deletion. So if your appl= ication involves many frequent insertions and deletions, then Red Black tre= es should be preferred. And if the insertions and deletions are less freque= nt and search is more frequent operation, then AVL tree should be preferred= over Red Black Tree. --Source GEEKSFORGEEKS.ORG</p> </div> <div [blog]: https://stackoverflow.blog/<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>"cl= ick here for updates" </pre> </div> </div> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab" id=3D"mdhelp-images"> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab--content"> <p>Images are exactly like links, but they have an exclamation = point in front of them:</p> <pre>![a busy cat](https://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/stackoverflow/= Img/error-lolcat-problemz.jpg) ![two muppets][1] [1]: https://i.imgur.com/I5DFV.jpg "tooltip" </pre> <p> The word in square brackets is the alt text, which gets dis= played if the browser can't show the image. Be sure to include meaningful alt tex= t for screen-reading software. </p> </div> </div> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab" id=3D"mdhelp-styles"> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab--content"> <div class=3D"col1"> <p>Be sure to use text styling sparingly; only where it hel= ps readability.</p> <pre>*This is italicized*, and so is _this_. **This is bold**, just like __this__. You can ***combine*** them if you ___really have to___. </pre> </div> <div class=3D"col2"> <p> To break your text into sections, you can use headers: </p> <pre>A Large Header =3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D Smaller Subheader ----------------- </pre> <p> Use hash marks if you need several levels of headers: </p> <pre># Header 1 # ## Header 2 ## ### Header 3 ### </pre> </div> </div> </div> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab" id=3D"mdhelp-lists"> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab--content"> <p>Both bulleted and numbered lists are possible:</p> <div class=3D"col1"> <pre>-<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>Use a minus sign for a bullet +<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>Or plus sign *<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>Or an asterisk 1.<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>Numbered lists are easy 2.<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>Markdown keeps track of the numbers for you 7.<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>So this will be item 3. </pre> </div> <div class=3D"col2"> <pre>1.<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>Lists in a list item: <span class=3D"spaces">    </span>-<span class=3D"space= s"> </span>Indented four spaces. <span class=3D"spaces">        </sp= an>*<span class=3D"spaces"> </span>indented eight spaces. <span class=3D"spaces">    </span>-<span class=3D"space= s"> </span>Four spaces again. 2.<span class=3D"spaces">  </span>You can have multiple <span class=3D"spaces">    </span>paragraphs in a list = items. <span class=3D"spaces"> </span> <span class=3D"spaces">    </span>Just be sure to inden= t. </pre> </div> </div> </div> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab" id=3D"mdhelp-blockquotes"> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab--content"> <div class=3D"col1"> <pre>> Create a blockquote by > prepending =E2=80=9C>=E2=80=9D to each line. > > Other formatting also works here, e.g. > > 1. Lists or > 2. Headings: > > ## Quoted Heading ## </pre> </div> <div class=3D"col2"> <p> You can even put blockquotes in blockquotes: </p> <pre>> A standard blockquote is indented > > A nested blockquote is indented more > > > > You can nest to any depth. </pre> </div> </div> </div> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab" id=3D"mdhelp-code"> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab--content"> <p> To create code blocks or other preformatted text, indent by= four spaces or surround with groups of backticks: </p> <pre><span class=3D"spaces">    </span>This= will be displayed in a monospaced font. The first four spaces <span class=3D"spaces">    </span>will be stripped off,= but all other whitespace will be preserved. ``` Markdown and HTML are turned off in code blocks: <i>This is not italic</i>, and [this is not a link](https://exa= mple.com) ```</pre> <p> To create not a block, but an inline code span, use backtic= ks: </p> <pre>The `$` character is just a shortcut for `window.jQuery`. </pre> <p> If you want to have a preformatted block within a list, ind= ent by eight spaces: </p> <pre>1. This is normal text. 2. So is this, but now follows a code block: <span class=3D"spaces"> </span> <span class=3D"spaces">        </sp= an>Skip a line and indent eight spaces. <span class=3D"spaces">        </sp= an>That's four spaces for the list <span class=3D"spaces">        </sp= an>and four to trigger the code block. </pre> </div> </div> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab" id=3D"mdhelp-html"> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab--content"> <p> If you need to do something that Markdown can't handle, use= HTML. Note that <a href=3D"https://meta.stackexchange.com/questions/1777/w= hat-html-tags-are-allowed" target=3D"_blank">we only support a very strict = subset of HTML!</a> </p> <pre>Strikethrough humor is <strike>funny</strike>. </pre> <p> Markdown is smart enough not to mangle your span-level HTML= : </p> <pre><b>Markdown works *fine* in here.</b> </pre> <p> Block-level HTML elements have a few restrictions: </p> <ol> <li>They must be separated from surrounding text by blank l= ines.</li> <li>The begin and end tags of the outermost block element m= ust not be indented.</li> <li>Markdown can't be used within HTML blocks.</li> </ol> <br> <pre><pre> You can <em>not</em> use Markdown in here. </pre> </pre> </div> </div> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab" id=3D"mdhelp-tables"> <div class=3D"mdhelp-tab--content"> <p> You can create tables using the <a href=3D"https://github.g= ithub.com/gfm/#tables-extension-">GitHub-flavored markdown format</a>. </p> <pre>| A header | Another header | | -------- | -------------- | | First | row | | Second | row | </pre> <ul class=3D"pl24 mt8"> <li>A header row is required and must be followed by a sepa= rator row with the same number of cells</li> <li>Cells are separated by a pipe (<code>|</code>) symbol</= li> </ul> <p> Set the <b>alignment</b> of a table column by placing a <co= de>:</code> on the left, right, or both sides of a separator in the separat= or line. </p> <pre>| left | center | right | |:---- |:------:| -----:| | One | Two | Three | </pre> </div> </div> <div class=3D"cbt"></div> </div> <div
